  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Promoting social stabilization through vocational training and job creation for vulnerable people and communities in post-Ebola Liberia</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">While Liberia is still on the way to recovery from the civil wars between 1989 and 2003, the recent outbreak of Ebola has seriously affected their path for recovery in an already fragile post-conflict setting putting a tremendous burden on the Government of Liberia.

Liberia heavily depends on the transnational corporations (TNCs) and their exports of rubber, iron ore and oil palm for growth, employment and fiscal revenues. Due to the plunge in the prices of these export commodities since 2014 and also unhealthy global economic environment, ArcelorMittal has laid off over 450 employees since January 2016, while the Putu Iron Ore Mining Company has reportedly shutdown and left. The rubber plantations put thousands of Liberians out of jobs and closed schools and hospitals run by them. However; Liberia does not have any other productive sector that can cushion these negative socio-economic impacts.

The proposed project aims to promote social stabilization by improving human security of the vulnerable people and communities affected by crises through promoting wood furniture industry and providing vocational skills to unemployed youth in close coordination with transnational corporations (TNCs).</narrative>
  </description>
